In early 2026, Vue quietly killed its own Virtual DOM. React, meanwhile, wrote a compiler to save it.
Those two sentences summarize the most interesting architectural divergence in frontend today. Two mature ecosystems looked at the exact same performance problem, wasted re-renders, and walked away with opposite answers. Vue 3.6 shipped Vapor Mode, which compiles components straight to surgical DOM operations and skips the Virtual DOM entirely. React 19 shipped a stable compiler that keeps the Virtual DOM but makes the manual optimization work disappear.
If you are making architectural decisions for a frontend team this year, you need to understand what is actually happening under the hood of both approaches, because the trade-offs are real and they will outlive whatever framework hype cycle we are currently in.
The Root Problem: The Re-render Tax
React’s default model is pull-based and top-down. When state updates in a component, that component and every child below it re-executes, unless you explicitly say otherwise. The framework then diffs the new Virtual DOM tree against the old one and patches only what changed.
The expensive part was never the DOM patching. The expensive part is that all the JavaScript inside those components, every filter, every map, every derived calculation, runs again just to discover that nothing changed. On a content page this is invisible. On a stock trading dashboard with high frequency data, or a large e-commerce app where adding one item to the cart wakes up unrelated corners of the page, this constant re-evaluation saturates the main thread.
Our industry’s answer for years was manual memoization. We wrapped everything in useMemo, useCallback, and React.memo, then spent afternoons hunting missing entries in dependency arrays. I call this the re-render tax, and by 2024 most large React codebases were paying it in both performance and readability.
Two architectural camps emerged to abolish that tax. SolidJS, Vue, Angular, and Preact converged on fine-grained reactivity, better known as Signals. React refused to change its model and moved the problem to build time with the React Compiler.
How Signals Actually Work
A Signal is, at its core, a reactive value that knows exactly who depends on it. When you place a Signal inside a template, the framework registers that specific DOM node as a subscriber. When the value changes, no component tree re-executes. The Signal walks directly to the text node it owns and updates it.
