import { createSignal } from "solid-js";function Counter() {
const [count, setCount] = createSignal(0); // This line runs exactly ONCE, when the component is created.
console.log("Component mounted."); return (
<button onClick={() => setCount(c => c + 1)}>
Count: {count()} {/* Only this text node ever updates */}
</button>
);
}The code looks almost identical to React, but click that button a hundred times and the console.log never fires again. The component function is not a render function that re-runs. It is a setup function that runs once and wires up a dependency graph.
One technical nuance that most articles get wrong: modern Signal implementations are not purely push-based. Solid, Vue, Angular, and the TC39 proposal all use a push-pull hybrid. When a source Signal changes, it pushes a “dirty” flag through the dependency graph, but derived computations stay lazy and only re-evaluate when something actually reads them. This is why Signal graphs avoid glitches and redundant intermediate calculations, and it is the detail that separates the current generation from the observable libraries of the 2010s.
Credit where it is due: Svelte pioneered the idea that reactivity belongs to the compiler back in 2019, and Svelte 5’s runes are Signals under the hood. The entire ecosystem has been converging on the same primitive from different directions.
The 2026 Scoreboard: Vapor Mode and the Great Convergence
The Signals camp did not stand still while React built its compiler.
Vue 3.6 made Vapor Mode stable in early 2026. Vapor compiles single-file components directly to imperative, fine-grained DOM operations with no Virtual DOM layer at all. Components mount faster because there is no vnode tree to construct, updates touch only the exact nodes that changed, and the vdom runtime disappears from the bundle. Crucially, Vapor is opt-in and incrementally adoptable: you can mark individual components or entire pages as Vapor while the rest of the app keeps running on the classic renderer, and the two worlds interoperate through an official plugin. The framework that helped popularize the Virtual DOM concluded that the future is not a better Virtual DOM. It is no Virtual DOM.
Angular completed its own transformation in parallel. Zoneless change detection became the default for new projects, and Angular 22 shipped Signals, Signal Forms, and the new reactivity APIs as stable in mid 2026. The old criticism that Zone.js re-checks half the component tree on every event is now historical trivia.
Here is the twist that most “framework war” articles miss: all three major ecosystems have converged on the same rendering future, fine-grained updates driven by Signals and compilers instead of runtime diffing. For real-world applications, raw rendering speed is no longer the deciding factor between React, Vue, and Angular. The war produced a winner, and it was not a framework. It was the idea of fine-grained reactivity itself.
Why React Said No to Signals
If Signals are this effective, why did React refuse to adopt them? The React core team’s position is a deliberate architectural stance, not stubbornness.
React insists that UI must be a pure snapshot of state at a point in time, flowing in one direction. Signals decouple state from the component lifecycle and make values live, mutable references that anything can subscribe to. That is precisely what makes them fast, and precisely what React considers a long-term maintainability risk in large codebases: reactive spaghetti where data flow becomes hard to trace.
There is also a deeper mechanical conflict. React’s Concurrent Rendering can pause, prioritize, and restart work in the background. A Signal that writes straight to the DOM mid-render can produce tearing, where different parts of the screen show different versions of the same state during one render pass. This is not a hypothetical: useSyncExternalStore exists specifically because external mutable stores clash with concurrent rendering, and React had to build a dedicated escape hatch for them.
So instead of changing your mental model, React changed your build pipeline.
The React Compiler: Optimization as Infrastructure
The React Compiler shipped stable in late 2025, and in 2026 it is the default assumption in new React projects, with built-in support in Next.js. It is not a runtime library. It is a build-time analyzer that takes your components, models them at the level of an abstract syntax tree, tracks which values depend on which inputs, and generates the memoization you used to write by hand.
