The code you write stays clean:
function ProductList({ products, filterText }) {
const filteredProducts = products.filter(p =>
p.name.includes(filterText)
); return (
<ul>
{filteredProducts.map(product => (
<li key={product.id}>{product.name}</li>
))}
</ul>
);
}What the compiler emits looks conceptually like this simplified version:
function ProductList(t0) {
const $ = _c(7); // memo cache slots
const { products, filterText } = t0; let filteredProducts;
if ($[0] !== products || $[1] !== filterText) {
filteredProducts = products.filter(p => p.name.includes(filterText));
$[0] = products;
$[1] = filterText;
$[2] = filteredProducts;
} else {
filteredProducts = $[2];
}
// ...same caching pattern for the JSX output
}Every value gets a cache slot, every computation gets a guard, and none of it exists in your source code. The compiler does this more accurately than you did manually, because it has full visibility into the data flow of the entire component.
Two honest caveats before you call this free performance.
First, the compiler only optimizes components that follow the Rules of React. When it detects a violation, it silently bails out and leaves that component unoptimized. The updated eslint-plugin-react-hooks now ships compiler-powered lints exactly for this, catching things like setState inside effects and invalid ref usage, so treat the linter as part of the compiler, not as an accessory.
Second, your old performance instincts are now liabilities. Manual useCallback wrapping in a compiled codebase does not just waste keystrokes. In some cases it interferes with the compiler's own analysis and produces worse output than writing nothing. The hardest part of adopting the compiler on a mature team is unlearning.
Signals Are Coming to JavaScript Itself
The strongest evidence that this debate matters is happening outside every framework: TC39 is working on standardizing Signals as a JavaScript language primitive. The proposal explicitly states that native Signals could power Virtual DOM frameworks, direct DOM frameworks, or hybrids of both.
Read that carefully, because it reframes the entire argument. Signals and the Virtual DOM are not competitors at the same layer. Signals are a state layer; the Virtual DOM is a rendering strategy. If the proposal lands, every framework will likely sit on the same native reactive core and differentiate purely on how it maps that graph to the screen. Ten years from now, createSignal may feel the way Promise polyfills feel today.
If you want to experiment with this model inside React right now without waiting for anyone, @preact/signals-react lets you drop Signal-based state into an existing React app and see fine-grained updates for yourself.
The Decision Framework
Press enter or click to view image in full size

There is no magic wand in software, only trade-offs priced against your project’s constraints.
Choose the Signals camp, meaning SolidJS, Vue with Vapor Mode, or modern Angular, when runtime performance is the product: trading dashboards streaming thousands of updates per second, real-time maps, canvas-heavy tools, animation-dense interfaces. Removing the diffing cost entirely gives the main thread room that no amount of memoization can match.
Choose React with the Compiler when you own a large, living React codebase or a team fluent in React’s mental model. Activating the compiler on an existing enterprise app delivers a performance upgrade without retraining anyone or rewriting anything, and that migration cost of zero is an architectural feature in itself.
And if you are starting fresh in 2026, be honest about one thing: for a standard CRUD or content product, all of these options are now fast enough that the framework will not be your bottleneck. Your team, your hiring pool, and your maintenance budget will be.
The manual optimization era of frontend is closing. Terms like useMemo are already fading from new code, and the real engineering conversation has moved one level up: should reactivity live in the language, in the compiler, or in the runtime?
So here is my question for the comments, and I want the honest answer, not the conference answer. Have you actually deleted your useMemo and useCallback calls after enabling the React Compiler, or are they still sitting in your codebase as a security blanket? And if you have shipped Vapor Mode or Solid to production, did the fine-grained model hold up once the app grew past fifty components?
